<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="452" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="51" pageNumber="452">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,151,176]" pageId="51" pageNumber="452">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ferro &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2018" box="[467,552,153,176]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Cardiacephala" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="452" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[467,552,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="452">spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Latin: thorny, prickly) refers to the “thorny” single spermathecae and paired spermathecal stems of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="452" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="51" pageNumber="452">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,223,248]" pageId="51" pageNumber="452">Comments:</emphasis>
This species differs from the similar 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bigot" authorityYear="1886" box="[765,939,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Calobata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="452" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camptomera">
<emphasis box="[765,939,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="452">C. camptomera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
mainly by its brownish colouration, unique paired spermathecal duct stems and single spermathecae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
